105
00:06:11,271 --> 00:06:14,239
   narrator: marseille soap is  
   a vegetable oil-based soap   

106
00:06:14,241 --> 00:06:15,473
        first handcrafted       

107
00:06:15,475 --> 00:06:17,509
        in the port city        
      of marseille, france,     

108
00:06:17,511 --> 00:06:19,511
       in the middle ages.      

109
00:06:19,513 --> 00:06:22,080
   this gentle hypoallergenic   
     all-purpose block soap     

110
00:06:22,082 --> 00:06:24,315
   became prized across europe  

111
00:06:24,317 --> 00:06:26,651
  for washing clothes, dishes,  

112
00:06:26,653 --> 00:06:30,154
 floors, and cleansing oneself. 

113
00:06:30,156 --> 00:06:31,623
                     ♪♪         

114
00:06:31,625 --> 00:06:33,759
    marseille soap is crafted   
            from just           

115
00:06:33,761 --> 00:06:35,594
  four traditional ingredients  

116
00:06:35,596 --> 00:06:39,931
 with no animal fats, colorants,
   perfumes or preservatives.   

117
00:06:39,933 --> 00:06:41,967
    it's still produced today   
         as it has been         

118
00:06:41,969 --> 00:06:44,703
    for more than 600 years.    

119
00:06:44,705 --> 00:06:47,972
      the four ingredients      
          are sea salt,         

120
00:06:47,974 --> 00:06:52,444
      water, on the right,      
          caustic soda          

121
00:06:52,446 --> 00:06:54,446
     and either coconut oil,    

122
00:06:54,448 --> 00:06:56,848
    palm oil or, most often,    

123
00:06:56,850 --> 00:06:58,316
        olive pomace oil,       

124
00:06:58,318 --> 00:07:00,652
         the second oil         
      extracted from olives     

125
00:07:00,654 --> 00:07:02,554
   after they've been pressed   
   to extract virgin olive oil  

126
00:07:02,556 --> 00:07:06,891
        for consumption.        

127
00:07:06,893 --> 00:07:09,761
 a worker releases the required 
        quantities of oil       

128
00:07:09,763 --> 00:07:12,130
        and caustic soda        
    into a cooking cauldron,    

129
00:07:12,132 --> 00:07:14,799
     then brings the mixture    
            to a boil           

130
00:07:14,801 --> 00:07:17,068
 while stirring for 1 to 2 days.

131
00:07:17,070 --> 00:07:21,440
the fatty acids in the oil react
  to the alkaline caustic soda, 

132
00:07:21,442 --> 00:07:24,609
  producing a thick soap paste  
      containing glycerin,      

133
00:07:24,611 --> 00:07:27,178
       a natural compound.      

134
00:07:27,180 --> 00:07:32,150
  this transformation is known  
       as saponification.       

135
00:07:32,152 --> 00:07:34,219
  workers add more caustic soda 

136
00:07:34,221 --> 00:07:39,625
     and cook to 248 degrees    
   fahrenheit for another day.  

137
00:07:39,627 --> 00:07:43,561
    they wash the paste with    
  saltwater two or three times, 

138
00:07:43,563 --> 00:07:45,630
each washing lasting half a day.

139
00:07:45,632 --> 00:07:49,067
          this removes          
    impurities and glycerin.    

140
00:07:49,069 --> 00:07:52,237
 without glycerin, the soap has 
     better detergent power     

141
00:07:52,239 --> 00:07:57,109
     to remove grease stains    
           on fabric.           

142
00:07:57,111 --> 00:07:58,910
 next, over the course of a day,

143
00:07:58,912 --> 00:08:01,446
  the workers repeatedly rinse  
     the boiling soap paste     

144
00:08:01,448 --> 00:08:03,414
        with freshwater.        

145
00:08:03,416 --> 00:08:06,451
then they let it set for 2 days.

146
00:08:06,453 --> 00:08:08,553
      they reheat the paste     
      for about 10 minutes      

147
00:08:08,555 --> 00:08:11,023
   at 158 degrees fahrenheit,   

148
00:08:11,025 --> 00:08:13,492
   just to resoften it enough   
          to be pumped          

149
00:08:13,494 --> 00:08:16,995
  to a series of super heaters. 

150
00:08:16,997 --> 00:08:20,031
                     ♪♪         

151
00:08:20,033 --> 00:08:23,769
the super heaters heat the paste
   to 230 degrees fahrenheit,   

152
00:08:23,771 --> 00:08:25,937
         liquefying it.         

153
00:08:25,939 --> 00:08:29,207
    as the liquid soap leaves   
     the last super heater,     

154
00:08:29,209 --> 00:08:30,742
   it passes through a nozzle,  

155
00:08:30,744 --> 00:08:33,678
      which sprays it onto      
    the walls of an atomizer.   

156
00:08:33,680 --> 00:08:37,449
   the atomizer cools the soap  
         under a vacuum,        

157
00:08:37,451 --> 00:08:42,554
       solidifying it into      
   a dry moldable consistency.  

158
00:08:42,556 --> 00:08:45,690
  motorized blades then scrape  
         the dried soap         

159
00:08:45,692 --> 00:08:48,293
    from the atomizer walls.    

160
00:08:48,295 --> 00:08:51,696
     the soap falls directly    
   into an extrusion machine,   

161
00:08:51,698 --> 00:08:56,968
        which works much        
       like a pasta maker.      

162
00:08:56,970 --> 00:09:00,538
   the machine forces the soap  
    through small round dies    

163
00:09:00,540 --> 00:09:03,141
       as revolving blades      
      chop it into noodles.     

164
00:09:03,143 --> 00:09:07,211
                     ♪♪         

165
00:09:07,213 --> 00:09:10,381
       as the soap noodles      
  fall into the conveyer belt,  

166
00:09:10,383 --> 00:09:13,018
     the soap workshop chief    
      inspects the quality      

167
00:09:13,020 --> 00:09:16,588
     by assessing the color,    
   the aroma, and the texture.  

168
00:09:16,590 --> 00:09:20,125
                     ♪♪         

169
00:09:20,127 --> 00:09:22,226
 at the company's in-house lab, 

170
00:09:22,228 --> 00:09:24,396
      a technician conducts     
      quality-control tests     

171
00:09:24,398 --> 00:09:28,800
        on samples drawn        
    from each production run.   

172
00:09:28,802 --> 00:09:33,104
    in this test, he measures   
  the percentage of pure soap.  

173
00:09:33,106 --> 00:09:35,240
      he weighs the sample,     
          then heats it         

174
00:09:35,242 --> 00:09:37,209
       in a microwave oven      
         for 10 minutes         

175
00:09:37,211 --> 00:09:38,910
 to evaporate all the moisture. 

176
00:09:38,912 --> 00:09:43,081
                     ♪♪         

177
00:09:43,083 --> 00:09:46,851
   this leaves only pure soap   
         without water.         

178
00:09:46,853 --> 00:09:49,521
     he reweighs the sample     
   to calculate the percentage  

179
00:09:49,523 --> 00:09:53,325
          of pure soap          
   as well as the oil content,  

180
00:09:53,327 --> 00:09:58,296
       which must be 72%.       

181
00:09:58,298 --> 00:10:00,932
   the factory sells a portion  
  of its marseille soap noodles 

182
00:10:00,934 --> 00:10:04,969
          to companies          
  who mold their own soap bars. 

183
00:10:04,971 --> 00:10:07,839
   it also molds a house brand  
           right here,          

184
00:10:07,841 --> 00:10:10,942
     compressing the noodles    
    into a homogeneous paste    

185
00:10:10,944 --> 00:10:14,679
         that extruding         
    the long continuous bar.    

186
00:10:14,681 --> 00:10:18,516
 an automated guillotine slices 
the bar into the selected shape.

187
00:10:18,518 --> 00:10:21,152
                     ♪♪         

188
00:10:21,154 --> 00:10:22,587
    the conveyer belt ferries   
            the cubes           

189
00:10:22,589 --> 00:10:24,856
    to the stamping machine,    

190
00:10:24,858 --> 00:10:27,925
   which stamps all six sides.  

191
00:10:27,927 --> 00:10:30,595
         each cube bears        
  the company's name and logo,  

192
00:10:30,597 --> 00:10:32,364
     the soap's oil content,    

193
00:10:32,366 --> 00:10:34,900
        and the savon de        
     marseille designation,     

194
00:10:34,902 --> 00:10:37,535
     attesting that this is     
        indeed authentic,       

195
00:10:37,537 --> 00:10:41,807
       traditionally made       
         marseille soap.        

196
00:10:48,582 --> 00:10:53,985
                     ♪♪         

197
00:10:53,987 --> 00:10:56,388
    narrator: for centuries,    
    people have migrated back   

198
00:10:56,390 --> 00:10:59,524
        and forth across        
   the french-spanish border.   

199
00:10:59,526 --> 00:11:01,960
         the traditional        
laguiole pocketknife is a result

200
00:11:01,962 --> 00:11:04,328
of the mixing of these cultures.

201
00:11:04,330 --> 00:11:07,666
it's a blend of an arab-hispanic
    knife, called the navaja,   

202
00:11:07,668 --> 00:11:12,737
  with a southern french knife, 
    known as the capuchadou.    

203
00:11:12,739 --> 00:11:17,141
   these are not pocketknives   
       for camping trips.       

204
00:11:17,143 --> 00:11:18,543
    they're high end cutlery,   

205
00:11:18,545 --> 00:11:22,513
   perfect for slicing through  
    delicious french cheeses.   

206
00:11:22,515 --> 00:11:27,051
  they feature the unmistakable 
 wavy pattern of damascus steel.

207
00:11:27,053 --> 00:11:31,255
    to recreate the legendary   
 metal known as damascus steel, 

208
00:11:31,257 --> 00:11:32,690
            a cutler,           
        who is an artisan       

209
00:11:32,692 --> 00:11:35,093
 who specializes in knifemaking,

210
00:11:35,095 --> 00:11:39,464
    stacks alternating layers   
   of nickel and carbon steel.  

211
00:11:39,466 --> 00:11:44,736
 he then uses a grinder to even 
  the edges for the next step.  

212
00:11:44,738 --> 00:11:47,372
    he welds the nine layers    
         of carbon steel        

213
00:11:47,374 --> 00:11:50,642
        and eight layers        
    of nickel steel together.   

214
00:11:50,644 --> 00:11:55,480
  he begins the forging process 
      by placing the layers     

215
00:11:55,482 --> 00:11:57,215
      in a coal-fired forge     

216
00:11:57,217 --> 00:12:02,287
       where they heat up       
  to 1,472 degrees fahrenheit.  

217
00:12:02,289 --> 00:12:05,457
    step-by-step, the layers    
         will be forged         

218
00:12:05,459 --> 00:12:09,627
       into a single piece      
       of damascus steel.       

219
00:12:09,629 --> 00:12:12,163
       an automated hammer      
       pounds the layers,       

220
00:12:12,165 --> 00:12:13,831
      forcing them to bind      
          to each other         

221
00:12:13,833 --> 00:12:16,801
     at the molecular level.    

222
00:12:16,803 --> 00:12:19,304
         as the powerful        
    hammering process forces    

223
00:12:19,306 --> 00:12:23,007
       the layers together      
 into a unified piece of steel, 

224
00:12:23,009 --> 00:12:25,843
      it also flattens out      
    and lengthens the metal.    

225
00:12:25,845 --> 00:12:29,046
                     ♪♪         

226
00:12:29,048 --> 00:12:32,150
       the cutler can then      
 break the piece in three places

227
00:12:32,152 --> 00:12:34,085
  and layer them all together.  

228
00:12:34,087 --> 00:12:38,556
     this triples the number    
    of layers from 17 to 51.    

229
00:12:38,558 --> 00:12:42,694
     the cutler will repeat     
  this process again and again  

230
00:12:42,696 --> 00:12:45,630
         until the steel        
     has around 300 layers.     

231
00:12:45,632 --> 00:12:50,001
                     ♪♪         

232
00:12:50,003 --> 00:12:52,470
     here, a cutler prepares    
          a specialized         

233
00:12:52,472 --> 00:12:54,405
 model of laguiole pocketknife, 

234
00:12:54,407 --> 00:12:59,877
         which will have        
      a distinctive shape.      

235
00:12:59,879 --> 00:13:03,214
he continues the forging process
    of heating and hammering.   

236
00:13:03,216 --> 00:13:06,718
   the carbon steel will give   
    the knife its sharp edge,   

237
00:13:06,720 --> 00:13:11,456
      while the nickel will     
      provide flexibility.      

238
00:13:11,458 --> 00:13:14,625
     this manufacturer uses     
   the forged steel to create   

239
00:13:14,627 --> 00:13:18,229
     several different types    
 of blades for its pocketknives.

240
00:13:18,231 --> 00:13:20,965
                     ♪♪         

241
00:13:20,967 --> 00:13:23,935
   a cutler places the formed   
        blades in an oven       

242
00:13:23,937 --> 00:13:26,004
     where the intense heat     
     will help flatten them.    

243
00:13:26,006 --> 00:13:28,473
                     ♪♪         

244
00:13:28,475 --> 00:13:30,308
    once a blade has cooled,    

245
00:13:30,310 --> 00:13:32,944
    a cutler cuts it to size,   

246
00:13:32,946 --> 00:13:34,913
      drills a hinge hole,      

247
00:13:34,915 --> 00:13:37,348
     and uses a belt sander     
       to reduce its width      

248
00:13:37,350 --> 00:13:38,983
  to about a tenth of an inch.  

249
00:13:38,985 --> 00:13:43,521
                     ♪♪         

250
00:13:43,523 --> 00:13:47,125
    next, a worker will heat    
   and rapidly cool the blades  

251
00:13:47,127 --> 00:13:49,961
         to temper them         
     before sharpening them.    

252
00:13:49,963 --> 00:13:53,364
     he then dips then into     
  a solution of ferric chloride 

253
00:13:53,366 --> 00:13:55,100
      to reveal the unique      
          wave patterns         

254
00:13:55,102 --> 00:13:59,637
     in the damascus steel.     

255
00:13:59,639 --> 00:14:02,974
  there's more to a pocketknife 
      than just the blade.      

256
00:14:02,976 --> 00:14:08,746
  this manufacturer hand crafts 
  each component of its knives. 

257
00:14:08,748 --> 00:14:12,750
to create the bolster component,
   a cutler starts by heating   

258
00:14:12,752 --> 00:14:15,219
       a third-of-an-inch       
      stainless-steel rod.      

259
00:14:15,221 --> 00:14:20,191
     once the steel reaches     
    1,562 degrees fahrenheit,   

260
00:14:20,193 --> 00:14:22,560
 he then stamps it into a mold. 

261
00:14:22,562 --> 00:14:26,931
     the production process     
    can stamp out 20 bolsters   

262
00:14:26,933 --> 00:14:28,800
       in just 12 seconds.      

263
00:14:28,802 --> 00:14:33,237
  once they've cooled, a cutler 
   spot-welds them to a blade.  

264
00:14:33,239 --> 00:14:35,940
                     ♪♪         

265
00:14:35,942 --> 00:14:37,275
   to shape the spring plate,   

266
00:14:37,277 --> 00:14:40,011
       which forms part of      
     the folding mechanism,     

267
00:14:40,013 --> 00:14:44,115
    a cutler heats one end up   
  to 1,562 degrees fahrenheit.  

268
00:14:44,117 --> 00:14:47,651
                     ♪♪         

269
00:14:47,653 --> 00:14:52,090
   he uses a specialized tool   
 to stamp the top portion flat. 

270
00:14:52,092 --> 00:14:55,159
    this flat surface will be   
 the starting point for cutlers 

271
00:14:55,161 --> 00:14:57,962
    to create the bee figure,   

272
00:14:57,964 --> 00:15:02,767
      an emblematic feature     
       of laguiole knives.      

273
00:15:02,769 --> 00:15:04,903
    workers start by reducing   
           the surface          

274
00:15:04,905 --> 00:15:07,872
     to a triangular shape.     

275
00:15:07,874 --> 00:15:10,008
         using a series         
       of different files,      

276
00:15:10,010 --> 00:15:11,676
  the cutler carefully sculpts  

277
00:15:11,678 --> 00:15:15,613
the bee's eyes, body, and wings.

278
00:15:15,615 --> 00:15:17,815
          it seems that         
      pierre-jean calmels,      

279
00:15:17,817 --> 00:15:19,551
          the inventor          
     of the laguiole knife,     

280
00:15:19,553 --> 00:15:23,421
   used a bee symbol in 1829,   

281
00:15:23,423 --> 00:15:24,956
         and the cutlers        
      have been using ever      

282
00:15:24,958 --> 00:15:27,792
  since to set the knife apart  
        from other types.       

283
00:15:27,794 --> 00:15:31,862
                     ♪♪         

284
00:15:31,864 --> 00:15:35,065
    cutlers shape the entire    
          spring plate,         

285
00:15:35,067 --> 00:15:36,667
        and it takes more       
        than skilled work       

286
00:15:36,669 --> 00:15:39,971
  with a few files to complete. 

287
00:15:39,973 --> 00:15:43,007
        stay tuned to see       
    how high-tech instruments   

288
00:15:43,009 --> 00:15:44,442
        refine the images       

289
00:15:44,444 --> 00:15:48,413
     before workers assemble    
     the rest of the knife.     

290
00:15:48,415 --> 00:15:50,448
        even the simplest       
         one-piece knife        

291
00:15:50,450 --> 00:15:55,587
     requires 109 production    
       steps to complete.       

292
00:15:55,589 --> 00:15:59,457
                     ♪♪         

293
00:16:06,399 --> 00:16:11,403
                     ♪♪         

294
00:16:11,405 --> 00:16:12,803
     narrator: in the 1820s,    

295
00:16:12,805 --> 00:16:15,306
          cutlers began         
 crafting laguiole pocketknives 

296
00:16:15,308 --> 00:16:17,174
       in aubrac, france.       

297
00:16:17,176 --> 00:16:19,577
  the tradition came to an end  
        after world war i       

298
00:16:19,579 --> 00:16:23,247
         but was revived        
       in the late 1980s.       

299
00:16:23,249 --> 00:16:26,917
  today, the artisans of aubrac 
blend time-honored craftsmanship

300
00:16:26,919 --> 00:16:31,655
    with advanced technology.   

301
00:16:31,657 --> 00:16:34,826
      to carve each unique      
  spring plate, a cutler starts 

302
00:16:34,828 --> 00:16:37,628
    by placing one in a vice.   

303
00:16:37,630 --> 00:16:41,232
   with the metal stabilized,   
 the cutler can focus on carving

304
00:16:41,234 --> 00:16:44,669
          with the aid          
     of powerful magnifiers.    

305
00:16:44,671 --> 00:16:47,872
      the tungsten carbide      
drill bits he uses are no larger

306
00:16:47,874 --> 00:16:51,209
        than four-tenths        
        of a millimeter.        

307
00:16:51,211 --> 00:16:54,278
      no wonder the details     
 on each spring are so precise. 

308
00:16:54,280 --> 00:16:57,282
                     ♪♪         

309
00:16:57,284 --> 00:16:59,851
      to temper the steel,      
       the cutler heats it      

310
00:16:59,853 --> 00:17:05,723
   to 1,886 degrees fahrenheit  
      for several minutes.      

311
00:17:05,725 --> 00:17:09,260
   next, he cools it suddenly   
        in a bath of oil.       

312
00:17:09,262 --> 00:17:12,563
      he will then heat it      
    to 446 degrees fahrenheit   

313
00:17:12,565 --> 00:17:15,600
     for 1 hour to complete     
          the process.          

314
00:17:15,602 --> 00:17:18,702
        this manufacturer       
     makes the knife-handles    

315
00:17:18,704 --> 00:17:20,771
    from different materials,   

316
00:17:20,773 --> 00:17:24,609
       including antlers,       
         wood and bone.         

317
00:17:24,611 --> 00:17:28,346
 when making a handle from bone,
  a cutler starts by slicing it 

318
00:17:28,348 --> 00:17:31,482
       into sections with       
      a specialized blade.      

319
00:17:31,484 --> 00:17:34,652
     he then cuts the slices    
      into smaller sections     

320
00:17:34,654 --> 00:17:39,591
   that approximate the sides   
       of a knife-handle.       

321
00:17:39,593 --> 00:17:42,493
    cutlers can use the bone    
     with its natural color     

322
00:17:42,495 --> 00:17:45,396
    or immerse it in a stain    
       for several hours.       

323
00:17:45,398 --> 00:17:48,733
                     ♪♪         

324
00:17:48,735 --> 00:17:51,068
      all of the components     
  for this laguiole pocketknife 

325
00:17:51,070 --> 00:17:52,403
          are complete.         

326
00:17:52,405 --> 00:17:55,273
  the cutler uses a belt sander 
       to give the spring       

327
00:17:55,275 --> 00:18:00,444
        a light sanding.        

328
00:18:00,446 --> 00:18:02,613
   next, using the same tool,   

329
00:18:02,615 --> 00:18:05,249
        he begins working       
   the bone handle components.  

330
00:18:05,251 --> 00:18:08,452
 with the framework of the knife
         as a template,         

331
00:18:08,454 --> 00:18:10,688
    he carefully reduces both   
        of the components       

332
00:18:10,690 --> 00:18:12,690
  to their required dimensions, 

333
00:18:12,692 --> 00:18:18,396
    achieving a perfect fit.    

334
00:18:18,398 --> 00:18:21,532
   with the metal as a guide,   
      he uses a drill press     

335
00:18:21,534 --> 00:18:23,134
  to pierce holes in the bone.  

336
00:18:23,136 --> 00:18:26,437
                     ♪♪         

337
00:18:26,439 --> 00:18:29,374
     with the practiced hand    
      of a skilled artisan,     

338
00:18:29,376 --> 00:18:31,742
        the cutler drills       
      the famed shepherd's      

339
00:18:31,744 --> 00:18:33,344
      cross pattern by eye.     

340
00:18:33,346 --> 00:18:38,315
 the shepherd's cross is another
  signature of laguiole knives. 

341
00:18:38,317 --> 00:18:40,551
                     ♪♪         

342
00:18:40,553 --> 00:18:42,486
 the cutler connects the spring 

343
00:18:42,488 --> 00:18:44,289
        to the components       
        known as scales,        

344
00:18:44,291 --> 00:18:48,292
     which form the internal    
     structure of the knife.    

345
00:18:48,294 --> 00:18:52,697
  to join the parts, he inserts 
      stainless-steel pins      

346
00:18:52,699 --> 00:18:54,799
      and hammers them flat     
         on either side         

347
00:18:54,801 --> 00:18:59,804
  to hold them firmly in place. 

348
00:18:59,806 --> 00:19:02,607
    he inserts short lengths    
       of thin steel wire       

349
00:19:02,609 --> 00:19:05,376
     into the holes drilled     
  to form the shepard's cross.  

350
00:19:05,378 --> 00:19:08,779
                     ♪♪         

351
00:19:08,781 --> 00:19:11,215
      he now begins adding      
      the bone side covers,     

352
00:19:11,217 --> 00:19:13,884
         which will form        
        the knife-handle.       

353
00:19:13,886 --> 00:19:17,254
  he carefully screws the bone  
  covers securely to the scales 

354
00:19:17,256 --> 00:19:21,325
   from the inside with three   
stainless-steel screws per side.

355
00:19:21,327 --> 00:19:25,863
                     ♪♪         

356
00:19:25,865 --> 00:19:31,702
   he then snips off the ends   
  of the screws that protrude.  

357
00:19:31,704 --> 00:19:35,806
       now, he can install      
    the damascus steel blade.   

358
00:19:35,808 --> 00:19:38,276
    he does this by inserting   
      a stainless-steel pin     

359
00:19:38,278 --> 00:19:41,145
     through the hinge hole.    

360
00:19:41,147 --> 00:19:43,147
       teflon washers will      
        keep the opening        

361
00:19:43,149 --> 00:19:46,050
      and folding operation     
     smooth and functional.     

362
00:19:46,052 --> 00:19:49,387
                     ♪♪         

363
00:19:49,389 --> 00:19:51,789
         the cutler uses        
       a specialized clamp      

364
00:19:51,791 --> 00:19:54,225
        to grip the knife       
     as he installs the pin     

365
00:19:54,227 --> 00:19:58,562
   at the back of the spring.   

366
00:19:58,564 --> 00:20:01,599
 this pin, together with the one
      that holds the blade,     

367
00:20:01,601 --> 00:20:03,334
 are the two essential elements 

368
00:20:03,336 --> 00:20:05,636
of the laguiole knife mechanism.

369
00:20:05,638 --> 00:20:14,678
                     ♪♪         

370
00:20:14,680 --> 00:20:17,749
                     ♪♪         

371
00:20:17,751 --> 00:20:19,017
      with the belt sander,     

372
00:20:19,019 --> 00:20:21,085
     the cutler now refines     
           the handle,          

373
00:20:21,087 --> 00:20:22,753
       smoothing the pins,      

374
00:20:22,755 --> 00:20:25,389
     and rounding the edges     
       of the bone covers.      

375
00:20:25,391 --> 00:20:29,026
                     ♪♪         

376
00:20:29,028 --> 00:20:32,996
  a final polish gives the bone 
 a shiny finish that highlights 

377
00:20:32,998 --> 00:20:35,833
  the iconic shepherd's cross,  

378
00:20:35,835 --> 00:20:38,235
    an innovation introduced    
       to allow shepherds       

379
00:20:38,237 --> 00:20:39,737
       to celebrate mass,       

380
00:20:39,739 --> 00:20:43,907
  even when far from a church.  

381
00:20:43,909 --> 00:20:47,111
a cutler puts an extra fine edge
      on the finished knife     

382
00:20:47,113 --> 00:20:48,512
 with the help of a belt sander 

383
00:20:48,514 --> 00:20:50,748
 that has a fine-grit sandpaper.

384
00:20:50,750 --> 00:20:55,653
                     ♪♪         

385
00:20:55,655 --> 00:20:58,756
 the cutler makes several passes
      on a piece of leather     

386
00:20:58,758 --> 00:21:00,291
      with a practiced hand     

387
00:21:00,293 --> 00:21:04,629
        to give the knife       
         its final edge.        

388
00:21:04,631 --> 00:21:07,765
     this knife is now ready    
  to join the legendary company 

389
00:21:07,767 --> 00:21:10,000
 of other laguiole pocketknives 

390
00:21:10,002 --> 00:21:13,571
      and peel a ripe apple     
   or slice some aged cheese.   

391
00:21:13,573 --> 00:21:17,275
          bon appétit.          

